<div id="outline-container-org4ea0527" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="org4ea0527">Poetry Vocabulary</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-org4ea0527">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org65a7c83" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org65a7c83">Elements</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org65a7c83">
</div>
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="org8d2bf98"></a>Stanza: a group of consecutive lines in a poem that form a single unit<br /></li>
<li><a id="org71825d2"></a>Meter: a regular pattern of stressed and unstressed syllables<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="orgdfcd330"></a>˘ /   ˘    /   ˘      /   ˘   /   ˘ /   ˘    /   ˘    /  ˘ /<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgacff883"></a>I do not like green eggs and ham, I do not like them Sam I am<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a id="org57c51cd"></a>Iambic pentameter: a line of poetry containing five beats: unstressed syllable then a stressed syllable<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="orgabcb6e1"></a>˘   /     ˘     /     ˘   /  ˘   /  ˘     /<br /></li>
<li><a id="orge412b4b"></a>But SOFT, what LIGHT from YONder WINdow BREAKS?<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a id="orge534607"></a>Rhyme: the repetition of accented vowel sounds following them in words that are close together in a poem (such as mean and screen). Not all poems rhyme.<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgbe33e4b"></a>End Rhyme: rhymes at the end of lines of poetry<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="org74ba6f6"></a>The world would end tomorrow afternoon<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgd4de7a3"></a>But short of that, it might be too soon<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a id="orgc3c4f29"></a>Rhyme Scheme: the pattern of end rhymes in a poem<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="org1686ef5"></a>Little Miss Muffet  a<br /></li>
<li><a id="org74e3314"></a>Sat on a tuffet a<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgc59e638"></a>Eating her curds and whey b<br /></li>
<li><a id="org0100ee2"></a>Along came a spider c<br /></li>
<li><a id="org29aef56"></a>And sat down beside her c<br /></li>
<li><a id="org5d73c7c"></a>And frightened Miss Muffet away b<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a id="org8bca361"></a>Internal Rhyme: rhymes within lines of poetry<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="org5e442ce"></a>Back in the chamber turning, all my soul within me burning.<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a id="orge31b477"></a>Approximate/Slant Rhyme: rhymes involving sounds that are similar but not exactly the same<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="org76033ef"></a>(such as leave/live)<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a id="org7dc9de6"></a>Refrain: a repeated sound, word, phrase, line, or group of lines<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="org27e1ee8"></a>“I gotta a feeling, that tonight’s gonna be a good night, that tonight’s gonna be a good night”<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a id="org4cf222a"></a>Quatrain: four lined stanzas of any kind—rhymed, metered, etc.<br /></li>
<li><a id="org3fe0f3b"></a>Prose: any writing that is not poetry<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="org090806d"></a>(essays, novels, short stories, etc.)<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a id="org6821688"></a>Couplet: two consecutive lines in a poem, usually rhyming<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="orgcb7a56a"></a>The outlook wasn’t brilliant for the Mudville nine that day;<br /></li>
<li><a id="org9f7009c"></a>The score stood four to two, with but one inning more to play;<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a id="org0ff6cd7"></a>Onomatopoeia: the use of words whose sounds imitate or suggest their meaning<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="org5167cd7"></a>(buzz, rustle, boom, tick tock, crunch, sizzle)<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a id="org1d7fc0d"></a>Speaker: the voice talking to us in the poem<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="orgc3b610c"></a>The voice is sometimes, but not always, the poet. Think of the <span class="underline"><span class="underline"><span class="underline"><span class="underline"><span class="underline"><span class="underline">__</span></span></span></span></span></span> (or the voice) as a character the author has created.<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a id="org39a2731"></a>Pun: a play on words, either on different senses of the same  word or on the similar sense or sound of different words<br /></li>
<li><a id="org5f5741f"></a>Assonance: repeated vowel sounds in non-rhyming words<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="orgd4a4f17"></a>He was way late to pick the grapes in May.<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a id="org6322bff"></a>Alliteration: the repetition of the same consonant sounds in words that are close together, or the repetition of consonant sounds that are very similar<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="orgd7652a0"></a>She stopped and stood still for a long time<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org2eb62f4" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org2eb62f4">Types</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org2eb62f4">
</div>
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="org03f58cf"></a>Ode: a lyric poem, rhymed or unrhymed, that praises something or someone<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgfe748cb"></a>Narrative: a poem that tells a story<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgc4ef04d"></a>Free Verse: a poem that has no pattern of meter or regular rhyme scheme<br /></li>
<li><a id="org0a92f68"></a>Lyric Poem: a poem that expresses the feelings or thoughts of a speaker; It does NOT tell a story<br /></li>
<li><a id="org211e51c"></a>Ballad: a song or songlike poem that tells a story mostly dealing with adventure or romance<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgf85b63e"></a>Elegy: a poem of mourning or grief, usually about someone who has died<br /></li>
<li><a id="org92148d4"></a>Sonet: a fourteen-line poem, usually written in iambic pentameter.  Shakespeare wrote these with a specific rhyming scheme of:<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="org567e376"></a>ABAB CDCD EFEF GG<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a id="org2b67244"></a>Lymeric: a very short humorous or nonsensical poem with five lines and an AABBA rhyme scheme<br /></li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>
